Sevan was a survey tradition practitioner remembered for inventing "condition-window dating" — a methodology for recording when observations were true rather than pretending permanence.
The innovation addressed a systematic flaw in Keeper-era survey documentation: records were written as if conditions at time of observation would persist indefinitely.
Sevan's method required every observation to include a declared condition window: the range of circumstances under which the recorded measurement remained valid.
A road-condition assessment under Sevan's methodology would specify not only current state but the seasonal, traffic, and weather conditions within which the assessment held.
Records with expired condition windows were reclassified as historical data rather than operative information — a distinction prior survey tradition had not formally recognized.
The methodology was initially resisted as adding unnecessary complexity to field documentation.
After several route decisions based on outdated survey records produced preventable failures, the condition-window approach gained institutional adoption.
Sevan's name appears in survey tradition literature primarily through the methodology, not through biographical detail — the practitioner is less documented than the practice.
The Witness Freshness Rule, developed in mountain legal contexts, applies analogous logic to testimony: records older than one active season require re-attestation before operative use.
Sevan's condition-window methodology and the Witness Freshness Rule are parallel developments from different institutional contexts that reached the same conclusion independently.
The Great Oasis Measuring House's calibration records adopted condition-window notation in the late Keeper era, linking Sevan's methodology to the corridor's primary measurement authority.

